New Photo Shows the Moon May Be Farther Away Than You Think  If the Earth were the size of a basketball, the moon would be a tennis ball some 24 feet away. Because of space considerations, illustrations almost always put them much closer together than they actually are.  A new photo from NASA may help to dispel these misconceptions. Captured by NASA’s OSIRIS-REx spacecraft when the Earth and moon were 249,000 miles apart, the image dramatically illustrates the distance. The Earth is a tiny mottled ball at upper left and the moon is little more than a grey speck in the lower right corner. Read more here.

Prince Philip Bows Out The 96-year-old husband of Britain’s #QueenElizabeth retired from public life on Wednesday with a final solo appearance at an official event, ending a royal career marked by occasional gaffes that landed him in hot water.  Though known for often off-color comments that seized the headlines, Philip has been by the queen’s side throughout her 65 years on the throne and she has described him as “my strength and stay.”  Above: Prince Philip removes his hat as he attends a parade at Buckingham Palace on Wednesday.   .  (📷 Hannah Mckay/Reuters)

The Making of an AstronautCountless Americans have dreamed of joining NASA’s exclusive club. When the space agency last asked for applications more than 18,000 hopefuls applied, shattering the previous record. . NBC News MACH made the trip to Houston and sat down with NASA astronauts Sunita Williams, top left, Kjell Lindgren and Karen Nyberg to dig deeper into what it takes to join the corps, train for the job, and then perform well under enormous pressure. (Photos: Dan Winters)  See the four-part series and a photo gallery on space travel by Dan Winters on NBC News MACH.

Iconic NY Anchor Had a Front Row Seat When Beatles Made History     New York reporter Gabe Pressman witnessed a lot in his more than 60 years of television broadcasting, but the photographic evidence that he had a front row seat to history was most dramatically captured when the Beatles arrived for their first trip to the U.S. in 1964.   Gazing up at the four shaggy-haired British lads, just above the microphones, Pressman stands out from the crowd of reporters. “Though few of us thought it at the time, we were witnessing the birth of an era,” said Pressman in 2014. The Beatles were greeted by a screaming crowd estimated at 5,000.  Pressman died Friday at the age of 93. See more here.   (Charles Tasnadi / AP)

Adam West, who defined the tights-wearing title role of “Batman” in the 1960s cult TV classic and remained a celebrated actor in the #superhero world, died Friday after a short battle with leukemia, according to his family. He was 88.   #AdamWest’s deadpan portrayal of #Batman brought the Caped Crusader into the national consciousness with a “bang!”   When West took on the tights, he stoked the stoicism for laughs: a superhero letting everyone know he was in on the joke.   “I just think I’m the luckiest guy in the world, really. I am,” he told Variety last year. “I mean, how many people get a chance to create an iconic character and one that goes on?”   (🎞 @imstilljulie / for @NBCNews)
